class Solution {
public:
    bool backspaceCompare(string s, string t) {
        string s1 = "";
        string s2 = "";
        int n1 = s.length();
        int n2 = t.length();
        stack<char>st1;
        stack<char>st2;
        for(int i = 0;i<n1;i++){
            if(s[i] == '#') {
                if(!st1.empty()) {
                    st1.pop();
                }
            }
            else st1.push(s[i]);
        }
        for(int i = 0;i<n2;i++){
            if(t[i] == '#') {
                if(!st2.empty()) {
                    st2.pop();
                }
            }
            else{
                st2.push(t[i]);
            }
        }
        while(!st1.empty()){
            char ans = st1.top();
            s1.push_back(ans);
            st1.pop();
        }
        while(!st2.empty()){
            char ans = st2.top();
            s2.push_back(ans);
            st2.pop();
        }
        return s1==s2;
    }
};

"Idea:
1. The idea is to simulate the typing process of both strings using stacks.
2. Each character is processed one by one from left to right.
3. If the character is a normal letter, it is pushed into the stack.
4. If the character is `'#'`, it represents a backspace, so the top element is removed from the stack if it is not empty.
5. After processing both strings, the stacks contain the final valid characters after all backspaces are applied.
6. The characters are then popped from the stacks and stored into new strings for comparison.
7. If both final strings are equal, it means both typed texts are the same, so return `true`; otherwise return `false`.
"

#Time Complexity:- O(n1+n2)                                       Space Complexity:- O(n1+n2)
